programme.title: Live - Wimbledon 2017
programme.desc: Day four of the third Grand Slam tournament of the year gets under way, featuring the men's and ladies' second-round matches. Day four last year produced mixed results for the British stars involved in the singles, with Andy Murray and Dan Evans winning, but Johanna Konta exiting in her first Wimbledon as a seeded player. Murray flew through his match against Lu Yen-hsun on Centre Court, losing just six games, but Konta lost to 2014 runner-up Eugenie Bouchard in a topsy-turvy encounter 3-6, 6-1, 1-6, while Evans caused an upset on Court Two against Alexandr Dolgopolov. The Ukrainian was one of several men's seeds to exit, including Dominic Thiem, David Ferrer, Gilles Simon and Ivo Karlovic, while the main news in the ladies' draw was the defeat of number two seed Garbine Muguruza(c)

programme.title: Live - Wimbledon 2017
programme.desc: Coverage of day five at the All England Club, where the men's and ladies' third-round singles matches are due to get under way. The rain intervened on day five last year to leave most of the matches unplayed, contributing to the decision to play on the middle Sunday for only the fourth time in Wimbledon history. The roof on Centre Court came into its own though, with Stan Wawrinka left cursing the draw, as he faced the unseeded Juan Martin del Potro, who was continuing his recovery from injury. This second-round match was finely poised throughout, but the Argentine secured the third set on a tie-break before going on to defeat the fourth seed in four sets. Another match that was in doubt for most of its duration was the only one to finish on Court One, as former champion Venus Williams edged through against Daria Kasatkina, winning 10-8 in the final set
